content.text: XML Namespaces
XML Namespaces provide a method to avoid element name conflicts.
content.html: XML Namespaces provide a method to avoid element name conflicts.

content.text: Name Conflicts
In XML, element names are defined by the developer. This often results in a conflict when trying to mix XML documents from different XML applications.
content.html: In XML, element names are defined by the developer. This often results in a conflict when trying to mix XML documents from different XML applications.

content.text: This XML carries HTML table information:
content.html: This XML carries HTML table information:

content.code_html:
<table>
  <tr>
    <td>Apples</td>
    <td>Bananas</td>
  </tr>
</table>

content.text: This XML carries information about a table (a piece of furniture):
content.html: This XML carries information about a table (a piece of furniture):

content.code_html:
<table>
  <name>African Coffee Table</name>
  <width>80</width>
  <length>120</length>
</table>

content.text: If these XML fragments were added together, there would be a name conflict. Both contain a <table> element, but the elements have different content and meaning.
content.html: If these XML fragments were added together, there would be a name conflict. Both contain a <table> element, but the elements have different content and meaning.

content.text: A user or an XML application will not know how to handle these differences.
content.html: A user or an XML application will not know how to handle these differences.

content.text: Solving the Name Conflict Using a Prefix
Name conflicts in XML can easily be avoided using a name prefix.
content.html: Name conflicts in XML can easily be avoided using a name prefix.

content.text: This XML carries information about an HTML table, and a piece of furniture:
content.html: This XML carries information about an HTML table, and a piece of furniture:

content.code_html:
<h:table>
  <h:tr>
    <h:td>Apples</h:td>
    <h:td>Bananas</h:td>
  </h:tr>
</h:table>

<f:table>
  <f:name>African Coffee Table</f:name>
  <f:width>80</f:width>
  <f:length>120</f:length>
</f:table>

content.text: In the example above, there will be no conflict because the two <table> elements have different names.
content.html: In the example above, there will be no conflict because the two <table> elements have different names.

content.text: XML Namespaces - The xmlns Attribute
When using prefixes in XML, a namespace for the prefix must be defined.
content.html: When using prefixes in XML, a namespace for the prefix must be defined.

content.text: The namespace can be defined by an xmlns attribute in the start tag of an element.
content.html: The namespace can be defined by an xmlns attribute in the start tag of an element.

content.text: The namespace declaration has the following syntax. xmlns: prefix =" URI ".
content.html: The namespace declaration has the following syntax. xmlns:prefix="URI".

content.code_html:
<root>

<h:table xmlns:h="http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/">
  <h:tr>
    <h:td>Apples</h:td>
    <h:td>Bananas</h:td>
  </h:tr>
</h:table>

<f:table xmlns:f="https://www.w3schools.com/furniture">
  <f:name>African Coffee Table</f:name>
  <f:width>80</f:width>
  <f:length>120</f:length>
</f:table>

</root>

content.text: In the example above:
content.html: In the example above:

content.text: The xmlns attribute in the first <table> element gives the h: prefix a qualified namespace.
content.html: The xmlns attribute in the first <table> element gives the h: prefix a qualified namespace.

content.text: The xmlns attribute in the second <table> element gives the f: prefix a qualified namespace.
content.html: The xmlns attribute in the second <table> element gives the f: prefix a qualified namespace.

content.text: When a namespace is defined for an element, all child elements with the same prefix are associated with the same namespace.
content.html: When a namespace is defined for an element, all child elements with the same prefix are associated with the same namespace.

content.text: Namespaces can also be declared in the XML root element:
content.html: Namespaces can also be declared in the XML root element:

content.code_html:
<root xmlns:h="http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/"
xmlns:f="https://www.w3schools.com/furniture">

<h:table>
  <h:tr>
    <h:td>Apples</h:td>
    <h:td>Bananas</h:td>
  </h:tr>
</h:table>

<f:table>
  <f:name>African Coffee Table</f:name>
  <f:width>80</f:width>
  <f:length>120</f:length>
</f:table>

</root>

content.text: Note: The namespace URI is not used by the parser to look up information.
content.html: Note: The namespace URI is not used by the parser to look up information.

content.text: The purpose of using an URI is to give the namespace a unique name.
content.html: The purpose of using an URI is to give the namespace a unique name.

content.text: However, companies often use the namespace as a pointer to a web page containing namespace information.
content.html: However, companies often use the namespace as a pointer to a web page containing namespace information.

content.text: Uniform Resource Identifier (URI)
A Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) is a string of characters which identifies an Internet Resource.
content.html: A Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) is a string of characters which identifies an Internet Resource.

content.text: The most common URI is the Uniform Resource Locator (URL) which identifies an Internet domain address. Another, not so common type of URI is the Uniform Resource Name (URN).
content.html: The most common URI is the Uniform Resource Locator (URL) which identifies an Internet domain address. Another, not so common type of URI is the Uniform Resource Name (URN).

content.html: Defining a default namespace for an element saves us from using prefixes in all the child elements. It has the following syntax:

content.text: This XML carries HTML table information:
content.html: This XML carries HTML table information:

content.code_html:
<table xmlns="http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/">
  <tr>
    <td>Apples</td>

content.text: This XML carries information about a piece of furniture:
content.html: This XML carries information about a piece of furniture:

  <width>80</width>

content.text: Namespaces in Real Use
XSLT is a language that can be used to transform XML documents into other formats.
content.html: XSLT is a language that can be used to transform XML documents into other formats.

content.text: The XML document below, is a document used to transform XML into HTML.
content.html: The XML document below, is a document used to transform XML into HTML.

content.text: The namespace "http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform" identifies XSLT elements inside an HTML document:
content.html: The namespace "http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform" identifies XSLT elements inside an HTML document:

content.code:
My CD Collection

Title Artist
content.code_html:
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<xsl:stylesheet version="1.0" xmlns:xsl="http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform">

<xsl:template match="/">
<html>
<body>
  <h2>My CD Collection</h2>
  <table border="1">
    <tr>
      <th style="text-align:left">Title</th>
      <th style="text-align:left">Artist</th>
    </tr>
    <xsl:for-each select="catalog/cd">
    <tr>
      <td><xsl:value-of select="title"/></td>
      <td><xsl:value-of select="artist"/></td>
    </tr>
    </xsl:for-each>
  </table>
</body>
</html>
</xsl:template>

</xsl:stylesheet>

content.text: If you want to learn more about XSLT, please read our XSLT Tutorial .
content.html: If you want to learn more about XSLT, please read our XSLT Tutorial.
